tweets.text: @IsabellaGhement @rstats_tweets I assume you wanted to use `tablefun_quoted`, this seems to work: https://t.co/LrCQFLelGs

a few days ago I asked for help, and last night @beninquiring (who's got a lot of figures similar to this in a really cool-looking dissertation) helped me solve this. 
The answer, for those interested, was 
+ geom_text(stat = "stratum", aes(label = Freq), nudge_x = -0.12) https://t.co/YGhfNz68lI https://t.co/mo9Mn4JpHs

@TimTeaFan @rstats_tweets Then I am applying this function with: 

R_DATA_EXPANDED_NEST %>% 
  dplyr::rowwise() %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(indigenous_counts = list(tablefun_unquoted(data, "gender")))

Using list2 will not work with what I am doing.

@IsabellaGhement @rstats_tweets Sorry for the confusion! I just like to use `rlang::list2()` because it prints really nicely when we use `dplyr::pull()` (it lets us name each list element). You can replace it with `list()` and the output should be the same (apart from the names).
@TimTeaFan @rstats_tweets Tim, I see you used rlang::list2().  I actually used just the plain old list(). Is that the source of my problems? I thought we could use just list().
